Description: CVE-2026-48959 - Fix algorithmic complexity DoS in IO::Uncompress::Unzip::fastForward
 The fastForward subroutine compared length($offset) (digit count of the
 decimal representation, always 1-19) against the requested chunk size
 instead of $offset itself. On crafted ZIPs with large STORED entries this
 collapsed 16 KiB reads to 1-19 bytes per iteration, causing CPU exhaustion
 when seeking past the entry to reach a named target.
 .
 Replace `length $offset` with `$offset` in the two clamp expressions.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/pmqs/IO-Compress/commit/68db44076f4c1a86a2ffe53a958eac6cabaf72e2
Author: Paul Marquess <pmqs@cpan.org>
Last-Update: 2026-06-09
---
--- a/cpan/IO-Compress/lib/IO/Uncompress/Unzip.pm
+++ b/cpan/IO-Compress/lib/IO/Uncompress/Unzip.pm
@@ -157,8 +157,8 @@
 
     while ($offset > 0)
     {
-        $c = length $offset
-            if length $offset < $c ;
+        $c = $offset
+            if $offset < $c ;
 
         $offset -= $c;
 
Description: CVE-2026-9538 - Cap entry size during read to defend against attacker-controlled size-field memory DoS
 The tar header's 12-byte size field is attacker-controlled. Archive::Tar's
 non-skip extract path allocates a Perl scalar of the declared size before
 returning the read-short error, allowing a few-KB compressed archive
 declaring a 100 GB inner entry to trigger immediate multi-GB allocation.
 .
 Adds $MAX_FILE_SIZE variable (default 1 GiB), checked once per entry in
 _read_tar, gating both chunked-skip and full-slurp branches. Set to 0 to
 disable the cap.
 .
 Adapted to Debian bookworm perl 5.36.0 (Archive::Tar 2.40), which predates
 upstream's $EXTRACT_BLOCK_SIZE / $EXTRACT_HARDLINK additions: the new
 $MAX_FILE_SIZE variable is declared after $RESOLVE_SYMLINK instead, and
 the matching POD section is placed after $Archive::Tar::ZERO_PAD_NUMBERS.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/jib/archive-tar-new/commit/f9af01426038e29d9578825a0cd3626946ab08c7
Author: Stig Palmquist <stig@stig.io>
Last-Update: 2026-05-27
---
--- a/cpan/Archive-Tar/lib/Archive/Tar.pm
+++ b/cpan/Archive-Tar/lib/Archive/Tar.pm
@@ -22,7 +22,7 @@ require Exporter;
 use strict;
 use vars qw[$DEBUG $error $VERSION $WARN $FOLLOW_SYMLINK $CHOWN $CHMOD
             $DO_NOT_USE_PREFIX $HAS_PERLIO $HAS_IO_STRING $SAME_PERMISSIONS
-            $INSECURE_EXTRACT_MODE $ZERO_PAD_NUMBERS @ISA @EXPORT $RESOLVE_SYMLINK
+            $INSECURE_EXTRACT_MODE $ZERO_PAD_NUMBERS @ISA @EXPORT $RESOLVE_SYMLINK $MAX_FILE_SIZE
          ];

 @ISA                    = qw[Exporter];
@@ -39,6 +39,7 @@ $DO_NOT_USE_PREFIX      = 0;
 $INSECURE_EXTRACT_MODE  = 0;
 $ZERO_PAD_NUMBERS       = 0;
 $RESOLVE_SYMLINK        = $ENV{'PERL5_AT_RESOLVE_SYMLINK'} || 'speed';
+$MAX_FILE_SIZE          = 1024 * 1024 * 1024;

 BEGIN {
     use Config;
@@ -442,6 +443,14 @@ sub _read_tar {

             my $block = BLOCK_SIZE->( $entry->size );

+            if ( $MAX_FILE_SIZE && $entry->size > $MAX_FILE_SIZE ) {
+                $self->_error( qq[Entry '] . $entry->full_path .
+                    qq[' declared size ] . $entry->size .
+                    qq[ bytes exceeds \$Archive::Tar::MAX_FILE_SIZE ] .
+                    qq[($MAX_FILE_SIZE); refusing to allocate] );
+                next LOOP;
+            }
+
             $data = $entry->get_content_by_ref;

 	    my $skip = 0;
@@ -2143,6 +2152,13 @@ zero padded numbers for C<size>, C<mtime> and C<checksum>.
 The default is C<0>, indicating that we will create space padded
 numbers. Added for compatibility with C<busybox> implementations.

+=head2 $Archive::Tar::MAX_FILE_SIZE
+
+This variable holds an upper bound on the per-entry declared size that
+C<Archive::Tar> will accept when reading an archive. Entries whose header
+claims a larger size are refused with an error before any read allocation.
+Defaults to 1 GiB. Set to 0 to disable the cap.
+
 =head2 Tuning the way RESOLVE_SYMLINK will works

 	You can tune the behaviour by setting the $Archive::Tar::RESOLVE_SYMLINK variable,
