 Description: Fix CVE-2026-13221 integer overflow in regex trie optimizer
 Perl_study_chunk optimizes an alternation of fixed-string branches into a
 trie and stores the delta between the first branch and the shared final TAIL
 in a 16-bit field. When an alternation has more than 65535 branches this
 delta overflows (CWE-190), producing a truncated/corrupt trie table with no
 error -- silently wrong regex matches, or a memory-corruption abort under
 `use re "Debug"`. This backports the upstream guard that refuses to build a
 trie whose first-branch-to-final-TAIL delta would overflow the 16-bit field,
 plus its bundled regression test (GH #23388).
 .
 In Debian's perl 5.36.0, regcomp_study.c does not yet exist as a
 separate file (it was split out of regcomp.c after 5.36); the fix is
 applied to the equivalent trie-optimizer path in regcomp.c. The
 regression test is inserted before the crash-test NOTE section in
 t/re/pat_advanced.t (the GH 20009 anchor used on 5.40 is absent here).
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/Perl/perl5/commit/03f74bbbd3a68350d926ee93d56ee4808c28c4c7
Author: Karl Williamson <khw@cpan.org>
Last-Update: 2026-07-16
Forwarded: not-needed
---
--- a/regcomp.c
+++ b/regcomp.c
@@ -4999,6 +4999,16 @@
                             tail = regnext( tail );
                         }
 
+                        /* The code below currently saves the difference from
+                         * start to finish in a 16-bit field, causing
+                         * GH #23388.  This defeats the design of batching
+                         * tries into chunks that each fit.  khw thinks it is
+                         * too late in the 5.44 cycle to relook at the design,
+                         * so for now anyway, don't make a trie that would
+                         * overflow */
+                        if (tail - startbranch >= U16_MAX) {
+                            continue;
+                        }
 
                         DEBUG_TRIE_COMPILE_r({
                             regprop(RExC_rx, RExC_mysv, tail, NULL, pRExC_state);
--- a/t/re/pat_advanced.t
+++ b/t/re/pat_advanced.t
@@ -2689,6 +2689,16 @@
     }
 
 
+    { # GH #23388
+        fresh_perl_is(<<~'PROG', , "", {}, "Avoid trie overflow");
+            my $x = join "|", "aaa".."mzz";
+            my $y = join "|", "naa".."zzz";
+            use re 'Debug';
+            "fnord" =~ m/(?:$x)|(?:$y)/;
+            PROG
+    }
+
+
     # !!! NOTE that tests that aren't at all likely to crash perl should go
     # a ways above, above these last ones.  There's a comment there that, like
     # this comment, contains the word 'NOTE'
Description: CVE-2026-42496 - Validate symlink and hardlink linkname in SECURE MODE
 Archive::Tar's SECURE EXTRACT MODE did not validate symlink/hardlink
 targets, allowing absolute paths or "../" traversal to escape the
 extraction directory. Reject such links unless INSECURE_EXTRACT_MODE
 is set.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/jib/archive-tar-new/commit/17c873492a05eddc0de18c1485e0b2cccd5a9158
Author: Stig Palmquist <stig@stig.io>
Last-Update: 2026-05-27
