Description: Fix CVE-2026-8376 heap buffer overflow in Perl_study_chunk
 A heap buffer overflow can be triggered when compiling a regular
 expression containing a repeated fixed string on 32-bit Perl builds
 (ptrsize == 4). Perl_study_chunk measured the joined substring buffer
 in characters instead of bytes; with a quantified fixed substring
 having a large minimum count, the byte calculation `mincount * l`
 could overflow SSize_t, leading to an undersized SvGROW allocation
 and an out-of-bounds write during the subsequent copy.
 .
 This patch adds an explicit overflow guard so that an oversized
 mincount * l raises a clean "Regexp out of space" error instead of
 corrupting the heap. The accompanying regression tests in
 t/re/pat_psycho.t exercise the original and a synthesised trigger
 (32-bit only - they use too much memory and are not vulnerable on
 64-bit builds). The test file gains a `use Config;` import so the
 `$Config{ptrsize}` check works under `use strict;`.
 .
 In Debian's perl 5.36.0, regcomp_study.c does not yet exist as a
 separate file (it was split out of regcomp.c after 5.36); the fix is
 applied to the equivalent Perl_study_chunk code path in regcomp.c.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/Perl/perl5/commit/5e7f119eb2bb1181be908701f22bf7068e722f1c
Author: Tony Cook <tony@develop-help.com>
Last-Update: 2026-05-27
Forwarded: not-needed

--- a/regcomp.c
+++ b/regcomp.c
@@ -5916,6 +5916,13 @@
                                                (U8 *) SvEND(data->last_found))
                                 - (U8*)s;
                         l -= old;
+
+                        if (l > 0 &&
+                            (mincount >= SSize_t_MAX / (SSize_t)l
+                             || old > SSize_t_MAX - mincount * (SSize_t)l)) {
+                            FAIL("Regexp out of space");
+                        }
+
                         /* Get the added string: */
                         last_str = newSVpvn_utf8(s  + old, l, UTF);
                         last_chrs = UTF ? utf8_length((U8*)(s + old),
--- a/t/re/pat_psycho.t
